I have no idea why you mock this video to be honest, unless it is a form of irony-poisoned "cope".

Encountering slaughter animals and realizing that a friendly, pure-hearted, intelligent creature died for your God-given food is a hard thing to do. It is good to meditate on this.

When I was like 11 years old I remember having to bring my favourite cockerel to be slaughtered. I cried, of course, but it had to be done. Such are the laws of our world. You are a predator, you were meant to be one, but you also do have a soul. Hunting is the basis of religion.

You are supposed to feel bad, to realize how predation is a symptom of the Fallen world. Would you be able to slaughter a baby calf? When it looks at you with its curious eyes, when it playfully rubs its forehead on your legs? And yet you do eat its flesh. How tragical life is!

Veganism, of course, is not the solution. But do you mock vegans out of strength, or as a way to cope? Have you realized how many cute, curious eyes faded into the abyss for your daily bread? It is a horrifying thought. It is good to meditate on this, anon, to fully realize it.

I am not suggesting you have to kill an animal yourself, I myself would hardly be able to. But the least we can do is purchase meat from local farmers and not from the vile industrion. To eat the flesh of beasts that had a good life, that saw the sky at least once in their lives.
And yet, we can be sure that the baby cow's feelings are true, and this is what matters most imo
Stay strong, Oto!

Pro-Saint Thomas Aquinas, but anti-thomism 

The vision of Stojan Adasevic proves to me the holiness of the saint, as ecumenical as it might be. "You are a good friend." - he said to Adasevic - even though he was an Eastern Orthodox Christian. Is Aquinas then not our friend too?
This, of course, is my personal take, I am not qualified to be your spiritual advisor, nor your priest, after all.

I have always been an enemy of logic and reason myself, but I will check it out. I guess if I had to form a take, it would be that Aquinas' work was a spiritual exercise, not that much unlike our Orthodox ones, that allowed him to get closer to God.

I hate sounding a bit traitorous, but I have always been annoyed by Orthodox brethren who felt a need to insult or besmirch catholic saints. It is a very aggressive mentality, and directly against Mark 9:38-41.
